  "answer": "Across all three parts of Bang-e-Dara (allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c, allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c, allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8), the corpus yields two poems that explicitly address the Prophet in direct second-person speech:\n\n1. **Part 3, Chapter 11 — \"Huzoor Risalat Ma'ab Mein\" (In the Exalted Prophet's Presence)** (allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8, chapter 11). This is the most fully developed Prophet-addressed poem. Iqbal narrates a visionary ascent: weary of the age's turmoil, he is brought by angels to the Prophet's court. The Prophet addresses him directly—\"O Nightingale of Hijaz's garden-bower\"—asks what gift he brings. Iqbal responds in second person (\"O Presence!\"), lamenting that no true loyalty remains in the world, and offers a phial containing the blood of Tripoli's martyrs (a direct reference to the Italian-Ottoman war of 1911–12) as testimony to the Ummah's suffering. The poem's occasion is historical-political (colonialism, Muslim decline) expressed through a transcendent, visionary frame.\n\n2. **Part 3, Chapter 16 — \"Qita\" (A Poetic Fragment)** (allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8, chapter 16). Iqbal narrates a scene of \"an anguished soul\" weeping at the Prophet's sacred resting place and speaking directly to the Prophet: \"who have remained strangers to You,\" \"May God save Your people,\" \"By corrupting Your Muslims.\" The address to the Prophet is explicit but mediated—Iqbal is the narrator, and the Prophet is addressed by the weeping figure. The occasion is criticism of corrupt Muslim leadership (specifically in Egypt and India) and a lament at the Prophet's grave.\n\nAdditional chapters reference the Prophet but do not directly address him: Part 3, Ch. 2 (\"Bilad-e-Islamiya\") calls Medina \"the resting place of the Chosen One\" in third person; Part 3, Ch. 23 (\"Tarana-e-Milli\") calls him \"The Prince of Hijaz\" in third person; Part 3, Ch. 20 (\"Shikwa\") is addressed to God, not the Prophet; Part 3, Ch. 6 (\"Ek haji Madinay ke raastay mein\") addresses \"Yathrib\" (the city) rather than the Prophet himself.\n\n**Do they form a coherent doctrinal cluster or vary by occasion?**\n\nBoth Prophet-addressed poems share a common doctrinal core: the Prophet is the supreme spiritual authority and guardian of the Ummah; Muslims are accountable to him; and the present state of Muslim decline is a kind of betrayal of that covenant. In both, the occasion is grief over the contemporary condition of Islam (colonialism in one, internal corruption in the other).\n\nHowever, they vary significantly by occasion and mode:\n- Ch. 11 is a sustained visionary-mystical poem (mi'raj-style ascent) with a historical-political payload (the Tripoli blood), cast as personal dialogue with the living Prophet across the veil of time.\n- Ch. 16 is a brief, politically acute fragment (qita form), lamentation at the grave, focused on betrayal by Muslim elites.\n\nThe two poems thus represent different genres (extended nazm vs. qita), different sites of encounter (heavenly court vs. the Prophet's grave), and different catalysts (imperial war vs. internal religious corruption)—but they converge on the same theological claim: the Prophet remains the living moral center of Muslim identity, and address to him is the natural form in which Iqbal voices the community's most urgent crises. They form a loose thematic cluster around prophetic intercession and Muslim accountability, but they are too few and too varied in form and occasion to constitute a tight doctrinal sub-corpus.",
